On 21 October 2012 18:57, Kirk T McDonald <kirkmcd@princeton.edu> wrote:
> Alan,
>
> I think you are "playing on words", and thereby missing the key point
> (stated yet another way at the bottom of this email).
>
> The notion of "capture area" tacitly means "maximum capture area".
>
> Any antenna can be "mismatched/detuned" so that the power received is much
> less than the maximum possible.
>
> No one (except you?) refers to the "capture" area of a badly tuned antenna
> -- as this is so small as not to be worth discussing.
>
> A small loop antenna can be tuned to capture the maximum possible power 
> with
> use of a ferrite.
>
> Adding a ferrite requires "retuning" of that antenna (via the tuning
> capacitor), but once it is retuned, the power captured is EXACTLY the same
> as before (if "losses" can be ignored).
>
> The ferrite does NOT change the maximum power than can be received, but it
> does boost the open circuit voltage [which increases the effective height 
> of
> the antenna and its radiation resistance, while leaving its effective area
> (capture area) unchanged.]
>
> -----------------
> It seems to me that you are claiming that the ferrite should get credit 
> for
> "tuning" the antenna, which process certainly increases the power 
> received.
> However, just adding a ferrite, but leaving out the tuning capacitor,
> actually results in LOWER received power, because the ferrite increases 
> the
> inductance, and the impedance of the antenna (when no tuning capacitor is
> present).    Without matching, the current, and power, in the load 
> resistor
> is lower than before.
>
> ------------
> ------------
> Your (true) arguments about open circuit voltage are irrelevant to the 
> above
> discussion.
>
> Adding the ferrite changes BOTH the open circuit voltage and the radiation
> resistance in such a way that the ratio Voc^2 / Rrad (and the power 
> captured
> by a "matched/tuned" receiver circuit) is the same as without the ferrite.
>
> --Kirk
>
>
